<br>
What exactly is the softcap and when is it.<br>
<br>
I dont really study my character, I just play em for fun, dont look on the interenet for any insights on how to build it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccccc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uxirys.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Xirys</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Monk-in-Training</span><br>  Posts: 54<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(8/22/02 8:50:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1807.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Heh..</span><hr size=1> A softcap is where even though you can get a visible number on the screen, such as Wisdom for example, higher, it does little or no good. So, for every point of Wisdom you add, you gain 10 mana. But once you reach 200 Wisdom, after that, you only gain 1  mana for each point. So your wisdom isn't capped, you can take it past 200, but you don't gain much benefit from doing so. So even though I can have 255 Wisdom which is a &quot;Hard Cap&quot;, i.e. I cannot have 256 Wisdom no matter how much gear I wear or buffs I get, the &quot;Soft Cap&quot; is 200. <br>
<br>
That's just one example. Here's another:<br>
<br>
There is also talk of a fixed AC soft cap, but many people, myself included, have come to believe this is a fallicy. There is a point vs. a given mobs ATK rating at which adding further AC will do no good. So if I'm fighting say, a bat in SolB, and my AC is 1250, the bat will hit me no less hard if I raise my AC to 1350. So I try lowering my AC, the bat hits no harder at 1150 AC. Same result. I try 1050 AC, same result. I try 950 AC, and now the bat is hitting me harder. I fiddle around and find that somewhere around 1050 AC, for the bat, is a &quot;Soft Cap&quot;. I can raise my AC higher on the screen, but it has no discernable effect.<br>
<br>
There are some mobs, especially in Luclin, that have ATK ratings so high, that you would need 4000 AC, or 8000 AC, (who knows?) before you started softening the blows they are dealing to you. So in this case again maybe 1350 AC is sort of a cap, but a cap on the high end of damage. So at 950, 1050, 1150, 1250, 1350, 1500, 1678, 1900 AC, etc.. I'm still taking the mobs max damage. So functionally, 950 AC does just as good as 1900 AC, as long 1900 AC is below the threshold where I start to diminish the amount of damage a mob is dealing to me. Since I can't get my AC high enough to diminish the amount of damage I'm taking, so I have a different kind of cap now. We just don't know what the low end number is on some mobs yet, because we can't get our AC high enough to start seeing the hits get softer, and thus find out the low end soft cap.<br>
<br>
There are other factors too, such as mitigation vs. avoidance, but it's extremely complicated, and you already have the right approach. Play the game, have fun, don't sweat the numbers too much. <br>
<br>
The current general consensus is that +HP gear is about as good as it gets.<br>
<br>
Hope this helped make this a little more clear. <br>
